"https://katowice.wyborcza.pl/katowice/7,35055,25295563,peadar-de-burca-the-joke-is-over.html",Peadar de Burca The Joke Is Over,"So here's the thing; there are Movies and there are Films. A Movie is the narcotic alternative to the reality of our lives, flighty, frivolous, childish, as opposed to the weightier, loftier beast that is Film. Perhaps yes, but also no.","The Movie/Film dichotomy has been traditionally viewed in terms of a choice between a greasy beef-burger and organic, locally sourced bean-sprout salad. Jaws is a cheeseburger Movie, in which we are given on-screen avatars who fight and kill the monster, thus imbuing the viewers with a triumphant yet transient feeling of power and courage. We are sated. We love its meaty flavour, but invariably we move on. White Ribbon is a Film whose purposeful ambiguity demands we ask questions about the roots of evil. It doesn’t fill us up. Haneke’s film nourishes us. It is generally accepted that Movies belong exclusively to the domain of youth, or at least to youth and their guardians who accompany them to that movie event par excellence – The Family Movie. Convention has previously always demanded that the Family Movie be safe, free from the contagion of controversy and devoid of pesky independent thought. Then came Pixar and Toy Story (a film made possible back in 1995 by the financial investment of Apple’s Steve Jobs) and animated, inter-generational entertainment became inventive, overtly painted in rich emotional colours, yet slyly tinted with cunning subversion. The message in the ending of Monsters University for example, where the heroes are expelled, rejects the traditional belief of third-level education being essential for a good life.",W kinie (Fot. Grażyna Marks / Agencja Gazeta),
